FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BOVINE - ISRAEL: OIE
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Sponsored by Elsevier, publisher of
Health Information for International Travel 2005-2006
<http://thelancet.url123.com/an9m7>
Date: 27 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Disease Information, Vol 18 - No. 51 [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_39.HTM#Sec1>

Foot and mouth disease in Israel
See also: 22 Oct 2004
(Date of previous outbreak of foot and mouth disease in Israel
reported to the OIE: March 2004).
Immediate notification report
Information received on 20 Dec 2005 from Dr Moshe Chaimovitz,
Director of Veterinary and Animal Health Services, Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Development, Beit-Dagan:
Report date: 20 Dec 2005.
Reason for immediate notification: re-occurrence of a listed disease
or infection in a country or zone/compartment following a report
declaring the outbreak(s) ended.
Identification of agent: foot and mouth disease (FMD) virus serotype O.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 20 Dec 2005.
Date of start of the event: 19 Dec 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Details of outbreak:
First administrative division: HaTsafon region
Lower administrative division: Tsefat district
Type of epidemiological unit: farm
Name of the location: Senir
Latitude: 33.23 N
Longitude: 35.67 E
Date of start of the outbreak: 19 Dec 2005
Species: bov
Number of animals in the outbreak
susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
520 / 15 / 0 / 0 / 0
Description of affected population: 15 calves in a feedlot of 520
vaccinated steers showed typical clinical signs. The calves in the
feedlot had been vaccinated only once against FMD, 6 months before,
with a polyvalent vaccine that included FMD virus strain type O.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: Kimron Veterinary
Institute, Beit-Dagan
Species examined: bov
Diagnostic tests used: - virus isolation on cell culture; - ELISA(1)
Date: 20 Dec 2005
Results: positive
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: Kimron Veterinary
Institute, Beit-Dagan
Species examined: bov
Diagnostic tests used: PCR(2)
Date: pending
Results: pending
Source of outbreak or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
(legal movement of animals?).
Control measures undertaken:
- quarantine;
- movement restriction within a 10-km radius of the outbreak;
- screening;
- zoning;
- ring vaccination (see details below);
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment.
Vaccination in response to the outbreak:
Location: Tsefat district (ring vaccination within a 10-km radius of
the outbreak)
Species: bov
Total number of vaccinated animals: ....
Species: o/c [ovine, caprine]
Total number of vaccinated animals: ....
Species: cml
Total number of vaccinated animals: ....
Details of the vaccine: O, A, Asia1 inactivated virus vaccine in oil adjuvant
Treatment of affected animals: yes (to prevent secondary infections).
Other details/comments: the outbreak occurred 5 km from the border
with Lebanon.
Final report: no.
(1) ELISA: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay
(2) PCR: polymerase chain reaction
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Last reported case of FMD in Israel was in March 2004. 6 months
later movement restrictions were lifted nationwide but unfortunately
it now seems to be back. - Mod.PC]
